@node intro "Welcome to StartSetup"

    @{b}StartSetup@{ub} is the program you use to create/delete menus and menu-items for the @{b}StartMenu @{ub}program.  It is also used to customize just about every other aspect of @{b}StartMenu@{ub}.
    
    @{b}StartSetup@{ub} was written by John Corigliano and is being placed in the public domain.
    
    @{b}StartSetup@{ub} requires MUI and OS 2.0+
    
    @{i}Use this software at your own risk.@{ui}
@endnode

@node tree "The Menu Tree"

    @{fg highlight}@{u}This Tree Thingy@{uu}@{fg text}

    When you run StartSetup, the menus are diplayed in a listview gadget in @{b}tree@{ub} form.  @{b}Menus@{ub} (items which open up to other menus) are displayed in bold and have an arrow character next to them.  @{b}Programs@{ub} (items that launch programs) are displayed in normal type.
    
    A tree can either be @{b}folded@{ub} or @{b}unfolded@{ub}.  If it is folded, the arrow will point to the left, and none of its children will be dsiplayed.  If it is unfolded, the arrow points down, and its children are visible.
    
    An example will explain this.  Every tree has the "Programs" menu as its root. Everything is added to the programs menu.  Now, suppose we add a menu to the "Programs" menu - call it "Text Utils". Then we add two programs to the "Text Utils" menu - "More" and "Ed".  If the tree were unfolded, it would look like this:
    
    @{b}v Programs@{ub}
        @{b}v Text Utils@{ub}
              More
              Ed

    "Text Utils" is a @{b}child@{ub} of "Programs".  "More" and "Ed" are children of "Text Utils".  "More" is a @{b}sibling@{ub} of "Ed" and vice versa.
    
    If we fold the "Text Utils" menu item (by double-clicking it), the tree would look like this:
    
    @{b}v Programs@{ub}
        @{b}> Text Utils@{ub}

    "More" and "Ed" are still in the tree, they're just not visible.
    
    If we saved this tree and started the StartMenu program, our menus would look like this:

    +-----------------------------------------+
    |   | Programs      >| Text Utils >| More |
    |   | System Prefs  >|-------------| Ed   |
    |   | Screens       >|             +------+
    |   | Commodities   >|
    |   | Edit Menu...   |
    |   | Find...        |
    | ------------------ |
    |   | Quit           |
    +--------------------+

    Now, let's add two siblings to "Text Utils" - "Clock" and "Calculator".  If the tree were unfolded it would look like this:
    
    @{b}v Programs@{ub}
        @{b}v Text Utils@{ub}
              More
              Ed
          Clock
          Calculator

    And our StartMenu looks like:

                         +--------------------+
                         | Text Utils >| More |
    +--------------------| Clock       | Ed   |
    |   | Programs      >| Calculator  |------+
    |   | System Prefs  >|-------------+
    |   | Screens       >|
    |   | Commodities   >|
    |   | Edit Menu      |
    |   | Find...        |
    | ------------------ |
    |   | Quit           |
    +--------------------+

    Lastly, let's add a sibling menu to "Ed" called "WP".  Then add a child program to "WP" called "Final Writer".  The unfolded tree is:
    
    @{b}v Programs@{ub}
        @{b}v Text Utils@{ub}
              More
              Ed
            @{b}v WP@{ub}
                Final Writer
          Clock
          Calculator

    And the StartMenu is:

                         +--------------------+
                         | Text Utils >| More | 
    +--------------------| Clock       | Ed   |--------------+
    |   | Programs      >| Calculator  | WP  >| Final Writer |
    |   | System Prefs  >|-----------------------------------+
    |   | Screen        >|
    |   | Commodities   >|
    |   | Edit Menu      |
    |   | Find...        |
    | ------------------ |
    |   | Quit           |
    +--------------------+

    I hope this makes sense!
@endnode

@node menus "Adding Menus"

    To add a new menu to the tree, the first step is to make sure the "Add" page is the current page.  Next, make sure the cycle gadget reads "Menu". The only string gadget that matters for menus is the one labeled "Name". Enter the name of the new menu in there.  The last step is to decide where you want to new menu to go.  To do this, hilight the menu or program in the tree that you want the new menu to be underneath. When adding to the tree, new items are always placed below the selected item.
    
    If the selected item is a program, then the new menu is added directly below the program (it becomes a sibling of the program).  For example, suppose we want to add a menu named "Graphics" to this tree:
    
    @{b}v Programs@{ub}
          File1a
          File2a
        @{b}v Menu1@{ub}
              File1b
              File2b
          File3a
          File4a

    If we hilight "File3a", enter "Graphics" in the name string gadget, make sure the cycle gadget reads "Menu", and click the "Do It!" gadget, the tree becomes:

    @{b}v Programs@{ub}
          File1a
          File2a
        @{b}v Menu1@{ub}
              File1b
              File2b
          File3a
        @{b}> Graphics@{ub}
          File4a

    If the hilighted item is a menu, we need to decide if the menu we are adding is going to be a child of the hilighted menu or a sibling.  A requester will ask you this question when you try to add something to the tree and the hilighted item is a menu.
    
    For example, using the tree above, suppose we want to make the new "Graphics" menu a child of "Menu1".  We would hilight "Menu1", then after we click "Do It!" tell the requester that will appear that we want "Graphics" to be a child of "Menu1".  The tree would then look like this.
    
    @{b}v Programs@{ub}
          File1a
          File2a
        @{b}v Menu1@{ub}
            @{b}> Graphics@{ub}
              File1b
              File2b
          File3a
          File4a

    However, if we tell the requester to make "Graphics" a sibling, the tree will turn out like this:

    @{b}v Programs@{ub}
          File1a
          File2a
        @{b}v Menu1@{ub}
              File1b
              File2b
        @{b}> Graphics@{ub}
          File3a
          File4a

    Do you see the difference?

    @{b}NEW!@{ub} As of v2.0 of StartMenu, menus can use custom brushes instead of the default menu icon.  Just use the @{b}Brush@{ub} gadget to select a brush to use when creating the menu.
@endnode

@node progs "Adding programs"

    Adding programs to the tree is very similar to adding menus, so you should read that section first.
    
    To add a program use the file gadget labeled "File" to select a program or script from your hard disk.  Once you select a file, all the other gadgets are filled in automatically.  However, if you are not happy with the settings, you may change them.  Here's what they are:
  
      @{b}Name@{ub}   - the name that will appear in the tree
      @{b}File@{ub}   - the program or script to run
      @{b}Dir@{ub}    - the directory that will be the program's Current Directory
      @{b}Brush@{ub}  - if this is suppiled, this is used instead of the program's icon
      @{b}Args@{ub}   - arguments to be passed to the program
      @{b}Output@{ub} - the standard output for the program.  Usually this is "NIL:" 
                 but you can change it to a console or regular file.
      @{b}Stack@{ub}  - amount of memory given to the program as its stack
      @{b}Pri@{ub}    - the program's priority when it is run

    Also, you need to make sure the cycle gadget is on the right setting:
        @{b}Menu@{ub}         - that's for menus, not programs
        @{b}WB Program@{ub}   - WorkBench programs
        @{b}CLI Program@{ub}  - CLI programs
        @{b}DOS Script@{ub}   - script files
        @{b}ARexx Script@{ub} - ARexx programs
    
    Note: if you use the asl file requester, all these values will be set by the program.

    After setting these values (or using the ones supplied), add the program just as you would add a menu.

    If you are adding a @{b}WB Program@{ub}, the @{b}Dir@{ub}, @{b}Args@{ub}, and @{b}Output@{ub} entries are ignored.  The program's "Current Directory" will be the directory in which it exists.  NOTE: it is okay to run a @{b}WB Program@{ub} as a @{b}CLI Program@{ub}.  However, if the program has any tool types, they will not be used.

    Problem: @{i}Sometimes the File button is disabled and I can't add programs!@{ui}
    Sollution: This happens when the @{b}Type@{ub} gadget is on "Menu".  To get the @{b}File@{ub} gadget enabled, just change the @{b}Type@{ub} gadget to anything but "Menu".

    Problem: @{i}Sometimes I can't set the Directory for a program!@{ui}
    Sollution: As mentioned above, when creating "WB Programs" only the Name, Brush, Priority, Stack, and File apply. All other information is taken from the program's icon - including the default directory.

@endnode

@node remove "Removing items"

    Removing items from the tree is very easy. Select the item to remove, go to the "Remove" page and click "Do It!".
    
    NOTE:  If you remove a menu, you remove @{b}ALL@{ub} of its children, too.
@endnode

@node edi "Editing Items"

    Editing an item is very easy.  First, select the item (menu or program) in the tree and click "Edit".  Change whatever needs changing and then click the "Do It!" gadget to record the changes.  If you decide you don't want to keep the changes, click the "Abort" gadget @{b}before@{ub} clicking the "Do It! gadget.
    
    NOTE: You cannot change a menu into a program and vice versa.
@endnode

@node move "Moving Items"

    Once an item is i tree, you can alter its location with the "Up" and "Down" buttons.  To move an item, first select it then press either "Up" or "Down".  Pretty simple, eh?

    Please note that you cannot move a program item out of its menu group. Also, when you move a menu, you move all of its children along with it.
@endnode

@node misc "The Misc Page"

    @{fg highlight}@{u}Window Geometry@{uu}@{fg text}

        @{b}Window Top Edge@{ub} and @{b}Window Left Edge@{ub} - these control the placement of the taskbar on the WB Screen.  If you want to use the default values enter @{b}-1@{ub}.

        @{b}Window Width@{ub} - this controls the width of the taskbar.  If you want to use the default value enter @{b}-1@{ub}.

        @{b}Icon Multiplier@{ub} - this controls the height of the icons in the menus.  This value is a real number that is greater than @{b}1.0@{ub}.  The default value is 1.25.
        This value is multiplied by the font height.  Then (for reasons known only to me :) the result is rounded to the nearest multiple of four (4).  For example, suppose you enter 1.25 and are using a font that is 15 points high.  The size of all the icons will be:

            1.25 * 15 = 18.75

        This is not a multiple of 4, so we round it to 20.  All icons will be 20 pixels high and wide.  You can use this information to create custom brushes of the exact size.

    @{fg highlight}@{u}Options@{uu}@{fg text}

        @{b}Commodities@{ub} - if this is checked, the "Commodities" menu will appear in the main menu.
        @{b}Screens@{ub} - if this is checked, the "Screens" menu will appear in the main menu.
        @{b}System Prefs@{ub} - if this is checked, the "System Prefs" menu will appear in the main menu.
        @{b}Logo@{ub} - if this is checked, a picture will be displayed in the main menu.
        @{b}My Computer@{ub} - if this is checked, the "My Computer" menu will be displayed in the main menu.
        @{b}Quick Refresh@{ub} - use this if you want @{b}StartMenu@{ub} to use the regular Background Pen of your WorkBench for the menus.  If you use this you cannot select the background color for the menus.  This may be useful if you find the menus open too slowly.

        For the clock, there are four (4) choices:
            @{b}AM/PM@{ub} - this will print a 12-hour clock with capital AM/PM. i.e. 1:50 PM
            @{b}am/pm@{ub} - this will print a 12-hour clock with lower case am/pm. i.e. 1:50 pm
            @{b}24hr @{ub} - this will printf a 24-hour clock. i.e. 13:50
            @{b}None @{ub} - choose this to turn off the clock.
    
        The "Popup" cycle there are two (2) choices:
            @{b}Auto@{ub}  - this will make child menus appear as soon as the cursor moves over the parent.
            @{b}Click@{ub} - with this, child menus will not popup until you click on the parent.

    @{fg highlight}@{u}Font@{uu}@{fg text}

        This uses a standard ASL requester from which you can select a font/size for @{b}StartMenu@{ub} to use.

    @{fg highlight}@{u}Menu Hi-Lite@{uu}@{fg text}

        This is where you can select the type of hilighting used for the menus:

            Bevel Box   - a reccessed box
            Rectangle   - a regular old rectangle
            Dotted Line - a dashed box
            Complement  - the colors are inverted

        If you find menu operations are too slow, don't use "Bevel Box".

    @{fg highlight}@{u}Spacing@{uu}@{fg text}

        This lets you control the amount of blank space between each menu item.  Its purpose is purely asthetic.
@endnode

@node prefs "The Prefs Page"

    This page lets you control which of the programs in the "Sys:Prefs" drawer show up in the "System Prefs" menu in the main menu.  If you have disabled the "System Prefs" menu (by un-checking the "System Prefs Menu" check box in the "Misc" page) then this page will be disabled.
    
    On this page there are two listviews.  The one labeled "All Prefs" is a list of all the programs in your "Sys:Prefs" drawer.  The other one, labeled "Start Prefs" is a list of the programs that will appear in the "System Prefs" menu.
    
    Below the "All Prefs" listview is a button labeled @{b}Add->@{ub}.  This takes the selected item and moves it to the "Start Prefs" listview.
    
    Below the "Start Prefs" listview are three (3) buttons:

        @{b}Remove@{ub} - removes the selected item
        @{b}Up@{ub}     - moves the selected item up in the list
        @{b}Down@{ub}   - moves the selected item down in the list
@endnode

@node colors "The Colors Page"

    There are actually two (2) Colors pages: one for OS 2.0 users and one for OS 3.0 users.
    
    However, both share the "Objects" group which contains a bunch of radio buttons.  To change the color of a certain object, select that object in the "Objects" group and then change the color.  The new value is automatically recorded.
    
    The Objects are :
    
        @{b}TaskBar@{ub}             - The main window's color
        @{b}StartButton Text@{ub}    - The text (if any) in the Start Button
        @{b}StartButtonBG@{ub}       - The color of the StartButton
        @{b}Menu Title@{ub}          - Text in menus
        @{b}Menu Title Select@{ub}   - Text that is hilighted in menus (only if using "Bevel" hilighting)
        @{b}Menu BG@{ub}             - Background of the menus (ignored if using "Quick Refresh")
        @{b}Menu BG Select@{ub}      - Background color of hilighted menu items (only if using "Bevel" hilighting)
        @{b}Clock@{ub}               - The digits in the clock
        @{b}Clock BG@{ub}            - The background of the clock
        @{b}Taskbar Button Text@{ub} - The text in buttons added to the taskbar
        @{b}TaskBar Button BG@{ub}   - the color of buttons added to the taskbar

    @{" Colors Page for 2.0 " link col2}
    @{" Colors Page for 3.0 " link col3}

    @{i}Notez Bien:@{ui} For some unknown reason (I blame MUI :) I mean, it can't possibly be a bug in @{i}my@{ui} program!), when you first go to the Colors page, the colorfield for the selected item (which will be the "Taskbar" object) will display the wrong color even though the silder(s) is in the right position.  Just select any other object then go back to the "Taskbar" object and the colorfield will be correct.
@endnode

@node col2 "2.0 Colors Page"
@toc colors

    If you are using 2.0 you get a slider that goes from 0 to (n - 1), where n is the number of colors of your WB screen.  Below the slider is a colorfield that displays the selected color.

    To change the color of an object, select that object then use the slider to select which color it will be.
    
    Example: To make the Clock's text appear in WB color #3 :
       
       1. Select "Clock" from the "Objects" group.
       2. Move the slider until it reads "3"
@endnode

@node col3 "3.0 Colors Page"
@toc colors

    If you have 3.0+ (hurray!) you get three sliders labeled "R", "G", and "B".  You also get a colorfield below the three sliders that diplays the current color.
    
    To change the color of an object, select that object, then move the R, G, and B sliders until the colorfield object displays the color you want.
    
    Example: To make the Clock's text appear in Yellow :
        
       1. Select "Clock" from the "Objects" group.
       2. Move the "R" slider to "255"
       3. Move the "G" slider to "255"
       4. Move the "B" slider to "0"

    @{b}WARNING:@{ub} @{i}"Danger, Will Robinson"@{ui}.  You have the ability to set any object to any one of 16 million colors.  However, if your WB screen is not "deep" enough (that is, only has 2 - 4 planes [4 - 16 colors]) @{b}StartMenu@{ub} might not be able to allocate all the colors it needs.  On a "deep" WB (5 - 8 bitplanes = 32 - 256 colors) this won't be a problem.
@endnode

@node locale "The Locale Page"

    @{i}Ok, so StartMenu is really localized yet.  But this will do for now...@{ui}

    This page is where you change the miscelaneous texts that appear in @{b}StartMenu@{ub}.
    
    First we have @{b}Start Button@{ub}.  There is a cycle gadget with three (3) choices :
        
        @{b}Text & Icon@{ub} - Both Text and an Icon are displayed in the "Start" button.
        @{b}Text@{ub}        - Only Text is displayed in the "Start" button.
        @{b}Icon@{ub}        - Only an Icon is displayed in the "Start" button.

    Next to that is a string gadget where you can enter the text that will be dsiplayed in the "Start" button (if you choose a text option).

    The next four things are places for you to replace certain other text items:
        
        @{b}System Prefs@{ub} - The label of the "System Prefs" menu
        @{b}Screens@{ub}      - The label of the "Screens" menu
        @{b}Programs@{ub}     - The label of the "Programs" menu
        @{b}Shut Down@{ub}    - The label of the "Quit" menu-item

    Lastly, there is the "Commodities Menu" group which is where you can change the various labels associated with the "Commodities" menus.
@endnode

@node quit "When you're all done"

    At the bottom of the window are two (2) buttons:
    
        @{b}Save@{ub} - this will save any changes made an then if @{b}StartMenu@{ub} is running, it will notify it that there have been some changes made and @{b}StartMenu@{ub} will reset itself.

        @{b}Quit@{ub} - this terminates @{b}StartSetup@{ub} without saving anything.  (Any saves made previously will still be recorded).
@endnode

@node tool "Using more than one prefs dir"

    Some people like to keep all the system files on one partition and everything else on another.  This is not such a bad idea.  Well, you can now specify more than one Prefs drawer for @{b}StartSetup@{ub} to search.

    To do this use the @{b}PREFS?@{ub} tooltype.  NOTE: You should replace the question mark ('?') with a number.  This allows you to have as many directories searched as you like.

    For example, suppose you have a prefs drawer called "Work:PrefsBackup" and one called "Misc:bin/OtherPrefs" and you would like @{b}StartSetup@{ub} to search these drawers (along with "Sys:Prefs") for prefs files.  Then add these two (2) tooltypes to the StartSetup icon:

        PREFS1=Work:PrefsBackup
        PREFS2=Misc:bin/OtherPrefs

    @{b}DO NOT@{ub} enter a tooltype for "Sys:Prefs".

    That's all there is to it!
@endnode
@end

